description:
Technically this might be Festuca brachyphylla because of the high elevation habitat, tightly bunched growth habit, and small anthers (ca. 1 mm).

The 2nd photo of the purplish and somewhat hairy flowering stems suggests this might be Festuca baffinensis, but this is supposedly known from the Rocky Mountains and not from the Sierra Nevada. Perhaps it could be Festuca brachyphylla because of the high elevation habitat, tightly bunched growth habit, and small anthers (ca. 1 mm). However, the the old leaves associated with the leaf bunch are characteristic of Festuca idahoensis, a species that is more widespread and more ecologically and morphologically variable than seemingly appreciated.

Photo documentation and species diagnosis at https://www.flickr.com/photos/plant_diversity/albums/72157688179026305

description:
Glyceria striata is a sporadic grass along riparian areas at the lowest elevations along the John Muir Trail. The species is distinctive because of its large size and broad leaf blades that uniquely combine with an open panicle of very small delicate spikelets (2-4 mm long). Glyceria striata has traditionally been considered a smaller statured grass with narrow leaf blades compared to G. elata.

Highest location for this species along the Skyline Trail.  Three plants seen at this location.

Lower Long Valley Creek is the only known location of this species at San Jacinto Mountain.  There appear to be many individuals in its canyon when it turns east and begins to drop precipitously, but that is a dangerous place to explore, now posted with "Do Not Enter" signs due to the hazards.

Fortunately, there are three shrubs in the south tributary from Hidden Divide that are easy to get to, shown in this and the previous observation.  But they are easy to miss unless you are looking for them!

Hall found a single specimen in his 1902 survey of San Jacinto, saying it was in a "canyon of the east side below Round Valley at an estimated altitude of 7500 to 8000 feet."  Hall was probably a bit confused as to where he was, since this is at 8300 feet elevation near Long Valley Creek.

Lower Long Valley Creek is the only known location where this species is abundant at San Jacinto Mountain (there are a few individuals in one or two other locations). description:
A common herb along the JMT occurs mostly at upper elevations. Here pale agoseris would go unnoticed except that it prefers trailside disturbances and produces conspicuous yellow flowering heads. The short stature of 1 dm or less tall is a function of the high elevation habitat.

Pale agoseris is a native perennial herb (4)8-50 cm tall that can thrive in good condition rangeland as well as disturbance-prone settings from low to high elevations. Individual flowering heads are scapose, the rays (ligules) are yellow, the pappus comprises only capillary bristles, and the achenes produce a beak 0.5-3 mm long.

description:
The common and widespread Salix arctica is conspicuous because of its long upright catkins and gray-green leaves with attenuate tips. Calamagrostis muiriana is the grass with purplish open panicles.

Arctic willow will is a subalpine to alpine mat-forming subshrub. It is perhaps the most common of the mat-forming willows and has small leaves that are usually just over 10 mm wide and about 10 mm long. The leaf tip is acuminate and the undersurface is light-green compared to the green upper surface. The styles are 1-2 mm long.

Artemisia spiciformis is similar to A. rothrockii and differs in its sagebrush gray green leaves (A. rothrockii has dark green leaves), larger stature, inflorescences distinctly ascending above a flattish canopy, and the dense gray-green leaf vestiture. Artemisia spiciformis differs from Artemisia tridentata, especially subspecies vaseyana, in having larger more well-spaced flowering heads, spindly stems, and main stem leaves that turn yellow by mid to late summer (because this is supposedly a deciduous species of shrubby Artemisia). All three of these Artemisia shrubs co-occur in this area.

description:
Like other herbaceous and subshrubby Artemisia, this species has a predilection for disturbance-prone settings. At higher elevations in this area this species integrades seemingly imperceptly into Artemisia michauxiana, which has more slender and greener leaf divisions. This site occurs along the JMT south of Le Conte Canyon at the junction of the Dusy Basin trail, Sierra Nevada, Fresno County, California.

White sagebrush is a native rhizomatous forb that ranges in stature 15-90 cm tall. Its generally rhizomatous growth form most likely facilitates its persistence in regularly disturbed settings including roadsides and overgrazed rangeland. The stem leaves vary greatly in width, length, and degree and depth of serrations and lobing, from entire leaves to dentate at the tip or lobed along the margins or highly dissected, as in ssp. incompta. In the last case, the dissected leaf segments measure at least 2 mm broad, in contrast to the similar Artemisia michauxiana, which has linear leaf dissections usually 1 mm or less wide.

description: July gold, Dedeckera eurekensis, White Mountains, elevation 1575 m (5165 ft). The only species in this rare shrub genus, July gold is related to Eriogonum in the Polygonaceae. It is found in only a few canyons with a strong carbonate bedrock component, in the mountains of Inyo and southern Mono counties, California. The species was first discovered in Eureka Valley, and presents huge masses of tiny golden-yellow flowers during the peak of summer heat when little else blooms, thus its common name. The plant in this photo is in fruit and late flower (open near center of image) at the end of August. The genus is named after Mary DeDecker, good friend and pioneering botanist and conservationist in the "Land of Little Rain." description:
hybrid scouring rush, Equisetum Xferrissii, White Mountains, elevation 1565 m (5135 ft).

From Hauke (1993, Flora of North America vol. 2): "The hybrid between Equisetum hyemale and E. laevigatum ... Although sterile, ... exists outside the range of E. laevigatum, and apparently it is dispersed vegetatively..."  In the White Mountains E. laevigatum is sometimes found in the same drainage, but often E. Xferrisii is the only scouring rush present.  No E. hyemale has been found in the range.

description:
fruits of spotted coralroot, Corallorhiza maculata, White Mountains, elevation 2195 m (7195 ft).

Members of this orchid genus are mycotrophic saprophytes (deriving nutrition entirely from decaying organic material via fungal intermediaries), and have no chlorophyll, leaves, or roots.  In the White Mountains found only in deep litter of water birch (Betula occidentalis) along permanent streams.

description:
creosote bush, Larrea tridentata, Beer Creek Fan, Deep Springs Valley, White Mountains, elevation 1655 m (5425 ft).

One of the farthest north (and highest elevation) creosote bushes I have encountered.  I know of 3 other isolated plants along the south edge of the White Mountains that are at slightly higher latitude.  In my opinion, these are more likely the result of recent successful dispersals, rather than remnants from past warm cycles.  The nearest continuous Larrea vegetation is less than 10 air miles to the southeast (and about 1000-2000 feet lower) in Eureka Valley.  Have encountered individual plants as high as 6000 feet elevation between the two locations.  Poised for climate change...?

description:
chaparral yucca, Hesperoyucca whipplei old fruiting stalks, White Mountains, elevation 1600 m (5245 ft).

This is a recently discovered northward range extension (or maybe more accurately, remnant of range contraction) for this species at the southern edge of the Great Basin in the White Mountains.  Only this single very healthy plant was found despite multiple further searches of the area.  The main range of chaparral yucca is in the southern Sierra Nevada and southwestern California chaparral, into northern Baja California.

Western Snowy Plovers (Charadrius n. nivosus) are small, federally threatened shorebirds that breed on open sandy beaches and lakeshores. We are fortunate enough in Monterey County to have a small year-round population that nest on our beaches and coastal dunes. Unfortunately, these small birds are susceptible to predation, disturbance, and nest destruction as their eggs are nearly invisible against the sand.
These plants were common in the narrow space between the coastal dunes and the old Salinas River Channel. Oregon Gumweeds are widespread along the coast of the western United States.

The next day, I saw a Yellow-winged Grasshopper (Arphia conspersa ramona), ID'ed via a short video clip showing it in flight and my Sierra Nevada field guide book.  That other grasshopper had the same "heart-shaped" bit on the upper thorax, so I'm thinking this is likely the same...  but unfortunately, my ID book only shows a small side view and the focuses on the wing coloration, so I could certainly be wrong.

Ugh! This camera is SO not up to the task, but this is an amazing photo, nevertheless. Lower right: A red slave-maker (Polyergus breviceps) is carrying a stolen pupa back into its cryptic home nest where it will hatch into a black ant (Formica sp., probably microphthalma), chemically imprint, and go cheerfully to work taking care of its red masters. Notice the carefully adapted red mandibles that grasp the pupa neatly and gently around the narrowing. Meanwhile, upper left, an exhausted red raider is carried home by a black slave. Ants are scary--no, make that horrifying--in their implications. Other photos: booty hand-off. Little girl defends!: chewing my cuticle and humping up to spray formic acid in the wound. Note: The range of what is currently considered P. breviceps doesn't extend westward beyond the Rocky Mountains. Source. More from James C. Trager: "...both genetic and morphological evidence lend support to the separation of P. umbratus from P. mexicanus. By the way, at Sagehen, Polyergus uses at least three (maybe four) different species of Formica as hosts, though apparently only one in any given colony. They are F. argentea, , F. microphthalma, and F. fusca, (and maybe F. accreta). In th[is] picture..., based on relatively sparse pilosity, and short and not very silvery appressed pubescence, and apparently rather small eye size, the host species is most likely F. microphthalma."
